    <div id="artwork-details">
    <div id="tombstone">

    <p>    Vladimir Ivanovich Ladiagin<br />
(Born 1910)<br />
Dem'ian Bednyi<br />
(Born Gubovka, 1883; died Moscow, 1945)<br />
    </p>
    <h3><em>Meet the Guests Accordingly</em>, TASS No. 0816, October 13, 1943</h3>

    <p>
    Stencil<br />    1648 x 954 mm<br />    The villager Khavrosh was a wild one. <br />
He fought with everyone without provocation. <br />
He took from others left and right. <br />
Foma had long been on his list of victims<br />
And so, one day, he broke into his house without invitation, <br />
Deciding to surprise him!<br />
But little did he know:<br />
Foma was not one to be reckoned with. <br />
Foma greeted Havrosh in such a manner<br />
That he could barely <br />
Crawl home<br />
With bloody bruises on his body.<br />
 <br />
The village marveled: <br />
“Have you heard about Havrosh? I bet <br />
He won’t have taste for other peoples’ beer anymore.”<br />
“Foma, you greeted him with fervor. <br />
He may not survive<br />
The treat you gave him.”<br />
“I greeted him as well as I could,”<br />
Foma replied with smile. <br />
“Not very well, but can one say?<br />
It depends on the guest. Meet the guest accordingly.”<br />
<br />
The Germans’ blood freezes when they hear news from the front. <br />
      They hadn’t anticipated such a treat.<br />
But what’s to say? We Russians have a custom – <br />
To greet unwanted guests in Russian manner. <br />
These “guests” have broken into our home as enemies: <br />
So “cook the pies to suit the guests”!<br />    Ne boltai! Collection, Obj: 205890</p>
        
        <!--<p id="dept-gallery">--><!--<br />-->
         <!--</p>-->
    </p>
    </div><!--/tombstone-->

